ducens nerve (CN VI)"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe visual pathway begins at the retina, where photoreceptors convert light into neural signals. \u003Cstrong\u003EThe optic nerve (CN II)\u003C/strong\u003E carries these signals from the retina through the optic chiasm to the lateral geniculate nucleus of the thalamus, which acts as a relay station. From there, the signals travel via the optic radiation to the primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe trochlear nerve (CN IV)\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the superior oblique muscle of the eye, controlling eye movement. It has no role in transmitting visual information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe oculomotor nerve (CN III)\u003C/strong\u003E controls most extraocular eye muscles and carries parasympathetic fibres to the pupil, but does not transmit visual information.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe trigeminal nerve (CN V)\u003C/strong\u003E provides sensory innervation to the face and motor innervation to the muscles of mastication. It has no role in vision.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe abducens nerve (CN VI)\u003C/strong\u003E innervates the lateral rectus muscle of the eye, enabling lateral eye movement. It does not carry visual information.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The optic nerve (cranial nerve II) carries visual information from the retina to the lateral geniculate nucleus.","Visual processing involves a complex pathway from retina through lateral geniculate nucleus to primary visual cortex in the occipital lobe.","The lateral geniculate nucleus acts as a relay station for processing visual information before it reaches the occipital cortex."],"references":["Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u2019s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Freddi TAL, Ottaiano AC. The Optic Nerve: Anatomy and Pathology. Semin Ultrasound CT MR. 2022 Oct;43(5):378-388. doi: 10.1053/j.sult.2022.04.006. Epub 2022 Apr 13. PMID: 36116850."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50314"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16364"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"50314","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/50314"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-24T21:15:32+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-24T21:16:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9055"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64880"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4930","links":{"self":"https://